.\" Manpage for quicsc
.\" groff -man -Tascii quicsc.1 | less
.TH QUICSC 1 "April 2026" "QUICS v0.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
quicsc \- QUIC client for secure file transfer and remote command execution
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B quicsc
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
[\fISERVER_ADDR\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B quicsc
is a client for secure file transfer and remote command execution over the
QUIC protocol with mutual TLS authentication. It uses X.509 client certificates
for authentication and can operate in both interactive and non-interactive modes.
.PP
The client supports file upload/download, remote command execution, and
execution of commands with specific user/group privileges (Linux only).
All communication is encrypted using TLS 1.3 over QUIC.
.SH CRYPTOGRAPHY
The client uses a hardened TLS 1.3 configuration with post-quantum hybrid cryptography:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Preferred key exchange: X25519MLKEM768 (X25519 + ML-KEM-768 hybrid)
.IP \(bu 2
Fallback curves: X25519, CurveP256
.IP \(bu 2
Cipher suites: TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384, TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256, TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256
.IP \(bu 2
TLS 1.3 only with mutual authentication
.IP \(bu 2
Forward secrecy enabled by default
.RE
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-s\fR, \fB\-\-server\-addr\fR \fISERVER_ADDR\fR
Server address (default: localhost:4242)
.TP
\fB\-C\fR, \fB\-\-client\-cert\fR \fICERT_FILE\fR
Path to client certificate (PEM format, default: ~/.quicsc/public.crt)
.TP
\fB\-K\fR, \fB\-\-client\-key\fR \fIKEY_FILE\fR
Path to client private key (PEM format, must have 600 permissions,
default: ~/.quicsc/private.key)
.TP
\fB\-a\fR, \fB\-\-ca\-cert\fR \fICA_FILE\fR
CA certificate to verify server (optional). Default: ~/.quicsc/ca.crt if present
.TP
\fB\-k\fR, \fB\-\-insecure\fR
Skip server certificate verification (for testing only)
.TP
\fB\-i\fR, \fB\-\-interactive\fR
Start interactive session (default: true)
.TP
\fB\-t\fR, \fB\-\-max\-idle\-timeout\fR \fISECONDS\fR
Maximum idle timeout in seconds (default: 120)
.TP
\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-keep\-alive\-period\fR \fISECONDS\fR
Keep-alive period in seconds (default: 15, -1 to disable)
.SH NON-INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
.TP
\fB\-u\fR, \fB\-\-upload\fR \fILOCAL_FILE\fR
Local file to upload to server
.TP
\fB\-d\fR, \fB\-\-download\fR \fIREMOTE_FILE\fR
Remote file to download from server
.TP
\fB\-o\fR, \fB\-\-output\fR \fILOCAL_FILE\fR
Output path for downloaded file
.TP
\fB\-c\fR, \fB\-\-cmd\fR \fICOMMAND\fR
Remote command to execute
.TP
\fB\-m\fR, \fB\-\-mode\fR \fIMODE\fR
Transfer mode: BIN or ASCII (default: BIN)
.TP
\fB\-e\fR, \fB\-\-env\fR \fINAME=VALUE\fR
Environment variable in NAME=VALUE format (can be repeated)
.SH EXEC COMMANDS (LINUX ONLY)
.TP
\fB\-X\fR, \fB\-\-exec\-cmd\fR \fICOMMAND\fR
Command to execute with specified user/group
.TP
\fB\-U\fR, \fB\-\-exec\-user\fR \fIUSER\fR
User to run command as ('-' for current user)
.TP
\fB\-G\fR, \fB\-\-exec\-group\fR \fIGROUP\fR
Group to run command as ('-' for current group)
.SH INTERACTIVE MODE
When started without non-interactive commands, \fBquicsc\fR enters interactive
mode with the following commands:
.TP
.B ! \fICOMMAND\fR
Execute local shell command
.TP
.B put \fILOCAL\fR [\fIREMOTE\fR] [ascii|bin]
Upload file
.TP
.B get \fIREMOTE\fR [\fILOCAL\fR] [ascii|bin]
Download file
.TP
.B exec \fIUSER\fR \fIGROUP\fR \fICOMMAND\fR
Execute command as specified user/group
.TP
.B cd \fIDIRECTORY\fR
Change working directory on server
.TP
.B \fIREMOTE_COMMAND\fR
Execute command on server
.TP
.B exit, quit
Exit interactive mode
.TP
.B help
Show help
.PP
Interactive features: arrow keys for command history, Tab for completion,
Ctrl+C to cancel line, Ctrl+D to exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Upload a file:
.B quicsc \-s server.example.com:4243 \-u /path/to/file.txt
.TP
Download a file:
.B quicsc server.example.com:4243 \-d file.txt \-o local.txt
.TP
Execute remote command:
.B quicsc \-c "ls \-la" server.example.com:4243
.TP
Interactive session:
.B quicsc \-s server.example.com:4243
.TP
Execute command as another user (Linux):
.B quicsc \-U www\-data \-G www\-data \-X "id" server.example.com:4243
.TP
With custom certificates:
.B quicsc \-C ~/certs/user.crt \-K ~/certs/user.key \-a ~/certs/ca.crt server.example.com:4243
.SH CERTIFICATE CONFIGURATION
Client certificates are automatically read from \fB~/.quicsc/\fR if available:
.nf
~/.quicsc/
- public.crt    # Client certificate
- private.key   # Private key (must have 600 permissions)
- ca.crt        # CA certificate (optional, loaded automatically if present)
.fi
.PP
Certificates can be generated using the server's built-in commands:
.nf
# On the server
quicsd create-cert --userid <userid> --name <name> --surname <surname>

# Copy to client
scp server:/etc/quics/certs/<userid>.{crt,key} ~/.quicsc/
mv ~/.quicsc/<userid>.crt ~/.quicsc/public.crt
mv ~/.quicsc/<userid>.key ~/.quicsc/private.key
chmod 600 ~/.quicsc/private.key
.fi
.PP
Alternatively, use the OpenSSL scripts in the \fIcerts/\fR directory:
.nf
cd certs/users/<userid>
./install-to-client.sh
.fi
.SH TRANSFER MODES
.TP
.B BIN
Binary transfer (default), preserves all bytes
.TP
.B ASCII
Text transfer with newline conversion (LF <-> CRLF)
.SH CONNECTION SETTINGS
.TP
.B Connection timeout
5 seconds for initial connection
.TP
.B Idle timeout
Configurable, default 2 minutes
.TP
.B Keep-alive
Packets every 15 seconds to maintain NAT connections
.SH FILES
.TP
.B ~/.quicsc/
Default client certificate directory
.TP
.B /etc/quics/certs/
Server certificate directory (CA and user certificates)
.TP
.B certs/users/*/install-to-client.sh
OpenSSL scripts to install user certificates (alternative method)
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR quicsd (1)
